14
0:00:38.720000 --> 0:00:42.960000
Thanks for inviting me to come and speak about this important topic today.

15
0:00:42.960000 --> 0:00:48.960000
We know there are a lot of discussions going on about formats for captions and we want

16
0:00:48.960000 --> 0:00:51.680000
to standardize them for the web.

17
0:00:51.680000 --> 0:00:55.440000
But standardizing it for the web has a much larger impact these days than just on web

18
0:00:55.440000 --> 0:00:56.520000
browsers.

19
0:00:56.520000 --> 0:00:59.280000
Just on the web itself, it goes into many different devices.

20
0:00:59.280000 --> 0:01:04.960000
So we're very interested and very keen to give a broad coverage of available technology.

21
0:01:04.960000 --> 0:01:07.560000
And this is what we're trying to do here today.

22
0:01:07.560000 --> 0:01:14.280000
So I'll be talking about mostly WebVTT, the file format.

23
0:01:14.280000 --> 0:01:18.560000
But I'll also be talking a little bit about how to plug that into the web browser, into

24
0:01:19.560000 --> 0:01:27.200000
HTML, so that in the future we have a very simple way of displaying captions in web browsers

25
0:01:27.200000 --> 0:01:33.280000
on videos without having to do much more than authoring a file and giving a link to the

26
0:01:33.280000 --> 0:01:36.160000
web browser for that file.

27
0:01:36.160000 --> 0:01:40.280000
So it will be very simple for people in the future to create more captions.

28
0:01:40.280000 --> 0:01:42.240000
All right.

29
0:01:42.240000 --> 0:01:48.720000
So this dig right in, as we were looking at requirements of a such a text format, a

30
0:01:48.720000 --> 0:01:55.760000
web text format for video, we looked at the different types of content that can be time

31
0:01:55.760000 --> 0:01:58.360000
aligned with video.

32
0:01:58.360000 --> 0:02:00.960000
And captions and subtitles are the obvious ones.

33
0:02:00.960000 --> 0:02:05.120000
But text video descriptions are also an important use.

34
0:02:05.120000 --> 0:02:11.720000
These are for blind users and can be read out by screen readers in parallel to the playback

35
0:02:11.720000 --> 0:02:13.120000
of the video.

36
0:02:13.120000 --> 0:02:19.960000
This may well not be the most usable way of doing audio descriptions, but it is a much

37
0:02:19.960000 --> 0:02:24.880000
easier way to publish audio descriptions for blind users.

38
0:02:24.880000 --> 0:02:29.200000
And in fact, for a lot of blind users, it may well be all they need because they already

39
0:02:29.200000 --> 0:02:34.720000
have their screen reader set up and it works really well for some people.

40
0:02:34.720000 --> 0:02:40.080000
Further to that, we are also talking about navigation or chapters, which is also very

41
0:02:40.080000 --> 0:02:43.280000
important for blind.

42
0:02:43.280000 --> 0:02:47.720000
And in fact, any user, if you want to go through a video quickly and find out what's

43
0:02:47.720000 --> 0:02:53.680000
in there, you want to jump to what we now know as chapter markers, we can call them

44
0:02:53.680000 --> 0:02:55.640000
navigation markers.

45
0:02:55.640000 --> 0:02:59.800000
This can be also covered with the same kind of format.

46
0:02:59.800000 --> 0:03:05.560000
And more generally metadata, this is something that archives are particularly interested

47
0:03:05.560000 --> 0:03:09.720000
in to attach metadata to sections in the video.

48
0:03:09.720000 --> 0:03:13.600000
Can also be done with such a time aligned text format.

49
0:03:13.600000 --> 0:03:18.440000
So what we have discussed for browsers is a very simple format.

50
0:03:18.440000 --> 0:03:22.520000
It's called Web VTT, video text tracks.

51
0:03:22.520000 --> 0:03:29.320000
Web VTT, this is one of the very simple files that we can think about, just a marker at

52
0:03:29.320000 --> 0:03:33.840000
the beginning of the file that identifies the file format.

53
0:03:33.840000 --> 0:03:38.640000
The captions or subtitles, let's call them Qs.

54
0:03:38.640000 --> 0:03:41.400000
Then have an individual identifier.

55
0:03:41.400000 --> 0:03:44.920000
In this case, it's the number one and number two.

56
0:03:44.920000 --> 0:03:46.720000
Could be any string, however.

57
0:03:46.720000 --> 0:03:52
And then we've got start times and end times on each one of these Qs and a piece of text

58
0:03:52 --> 0:03:53.720000
in there.

59
0:03:53.720000 --> 0:04:00.640000
It turns out then, as we all know, how captions are displayed on screen in something like

60
0:04:00.640000 --> 0:04:07.120000
this, if it's automatically created by the browser.

61
0:04:07.120000 --> 0:04:11.040000
That was the very simplest way of doing subtitles.

62
0:04:11.040000 --> 0:04:16.480000
Now we want to do more than just the simple captions, in particular if we want to achieve

63
0:04:16.480000 --> 0:04:22.120000
all the functionality of, for example, the CEA 608 captions, then we need to do a bit

64
0:04:22.160000 --> 0:04:23.760000
more than just text.

65
0:04:23.760000 --> 0:04:25.920000
We also want to have some formatting in there.

66
0:04:25.920000 --> 0:04:30.240000
Here is an example on how to do bold.

67
0:04:30.240000 --> 0:04:32.800000
I'll point to it.

68
0:04:32.800000 --> 0:04:37.320000
There's a bold tag in here, so that will be bold text.

69
0:04:37.320000 --> 0:04:39.760000
Here is some italic text.

70
0:04:39.760000 --> 0:04:48.520000
And up here, we've got a general way to associate style or a class to a piece of text and give

71
0:04:48.520000 --> 0:04:49.520000
it a meaning.

72
0:04:49.520000 --> 0:04:59.280000
In this situation, we've turned a piece of text into red text and capitalized it.

73
0:04:59.280000 --> 0:05:05.640000
Of course, if we're using this format also for subtitles, we need to be careful to cover

74
0:05:05.640000 --> 0:05:07.800000
internationalization issues.

75
0:05:07.800000 --> 0:05:10.120000
Web VTT is very clear here.

76
0:05:10.120000 --> 0:05:13.760000
It requires UTF-8 character encoding.

77
0:05:13.760000 --> 0:05:20.760000
It has a Ruby tag, which supports Asian languages in particular.

78
0:05:20.760000 --> 0:05:25.680000
It also does vertical and horizontal rendering of text.

79
0:05:25.680000 --> 0:05:30.640000
Again, possibly one of the most important ones are Asian languages.

80
0:05:30.640000 --> 0:05:35.600000
And I think there are a few other languages that are also rendered vertically.

81
0:05:35.600000 --> 0:05:38.960000
And we need to make sure we get the alignment right.

82
0:05:39.960000 --> 0:05:45.200000
And the text is red from the right to the left, so therefore it needs to be aligned on

83
0:05:45.200000 --> 0:05:51.360000
the right rather than on the left.

84
0:05:51.360000 --> 0:05:54.640000
Now positioning is another requirement.

85
0:05:54.640000 --> 0:06:01.160000
Again, something that traditional captions, TV captions, are able to do.

86
0:06:01.160000 --> 0:06:06.440000
It's possible to position cues anywhere in VTT.

87
0:06:06.440000 --> 0:06:10.880000
There are basically three important ways to position text.

88
0:06:10.880000 --> 0:06:12.840000
There are line positions.

89
0:06:12.840000 --> 0:06:19.280000
So the concept of display lines exists in Web VTT.

90
0:06:19.280000 --> 0:06:25.760000
So the line position allows people to directly address a specific line.

91
0:06:25.760000 --> 0:06:31.760000
It's also, it can be done with a line number or a percentage.

92
0:06:31.760000 --> 0:06:34.720000
Then we have the text position.

93
0:06:34.720000 --> 0:06:41.080000
This means we're placing the text either on the left and the middle or on the right.

94
0:06:41.080000 --> 0:06:44.960000
No, hold on, that's the alignment, sorry.

95
0:06:44.960000 --> 0:06:46.800000
Alignment is left, middle and right.

96
0:06:46.800000 --> 0:06:56.400000
And the text position is, so when we have text like this, it's in the middle and it's

97
0:06:56.400000 --> 0:06:57.400000
centered.

98
0:06:57.400000 --> 0:07:05.760000
So we can also do a centering and we can do a left alignment and the right alignment,

99
0:07:05.760000 --> 0:07:09.120000
but we can also move that whole text elsewhere.

100
0:07:09.120000 --> 0:07:12.920000
So the text position is where we move the text and the alignment is where we align it

101
0:07:12.920000 --> 0:07:14.720000
at.

102
0:07:14.720000 --> 0:07:18.120000
Sorry for the confusion.

103
0:07:18.120000 --> 0:07:23.880000
We also have speaker semantics included into Web VTT, which is interesting because it allows

104
0:07:23.960000 --> 0:07:27.720000
us to put some semantic information into our markup.

105
0:07:27.720000 --> 0:07:30.680000
Here for example, we have two people speaking.

106
0:07:30.680000 --> 0:07:35
We know they're positioned on the left and on the right.

107
0:07:35 --> 0:07:43.440000
And the speaker markup can tell us where we want to position it and can also, for example,

108
0:07:43.440000 --> 0:07:47.840000
help us always use the same styling for the same speaker.

109
0:07:47.840000 --> 0:07:53.560000
So for example, we want to use the same font, the same font color, maybe a specific outline

110
0:07:53.640000 --> 0:07:54.840000
or something for a speaker.

111
0:07:54.840000 --> 0:08:01.760000
We can define that and then apply that always for that speaker.

112
0:08:01.760000 --> 0:08:04.920000
Now so much for captions.

113
0:08:04.920000 --> 0:08:09.480000
Now we move on to a little example on text descriptions.

114
0:08:09.480000 --> 0:08:20.320000
Here is one that I've used previously and we've got that as an example on the side.

115
0:08:20.320000 --> 0:08:21.760000
I'm not going to go there.

116
0:08:21.760000 --> 0:08:25.520000
I just want to mention it because we want to focus on captions today.

117
0:08:25.520000 --> 0:08:33.280000
But what happens here is we've got text that's aligned with start and end time as well.

118
0:08:33.280000 --> 0:08:41.560000
And for a typical word rate of a screen reader, it will fit into that space and it will be

119
0:08:41.560000 --> 0:08:48.440000
read back by the screen reader during that time.

120
0:08:49.440000 --> 0:08:52.720000
Here is the navigation example.

121
0:08:52.720000 --> 0:08:56.600000
As I mentioned, Web VTT can also be used for navigation.

122
0:08:56.600000 --> 0:09:03
Here we have three chapters and we can directly jump from chapter to chapter.

123
0:09:03 --> 0:09:07.840000
There needs to be extra controls on videos to support this but this is something we're

124
0:09:07.840000 --> 0:09:11.080000
working towards.

125
0:09:11.080000 --> 0:09:17
Now of course, as I'm saying, controls and input into web pages and automatic rendering,

126
0:09:17 --> 0:09:19.120000
we need to know how we're going to do that.

127
0:09:19.120000 --> 0:09:29
And there is markup in HTML5 for associating captions and formats like this with videos.

128
0:09:29 --> 0:09:35.960000
In this example, I've got all of the VTT files that we've used before.

129
0:09:35.960000 --> 0:09:41.560000
I've included them here and what we're using for it is called a track element.

130
0:09:41.560000 --> 0:09:48
And this track element is included underneath the video element in the HTML5 markup.

131
0:09:48 --> 0:09:55.240000
It links to the VTT file and there is some description possible for the type of file

132
0:09:55.240000 --> 0:09:56.240000
it is.

133
0:09:56.240000 --> 0:09:57.880000
So we have a label.

134
0:09:57.880000 --> 0:10:00.200000
In this case, it's an English caption.

135
0:10:00.200000 --> 0:10:10.560000
We have a kind which gives us a means to group all the tracks of the same type together.

136
0:10:10.560000 --> 0:10:15.760000
And we identify the language because of course when we have user settings in browsers, we

137
0:10:15.760000 --> 0:10:22.120000
want to automatically make certain tracks available to the user.

138
0:10:22.120000 --> 0:10:27.160000
If the user has, for example, said that they always want captions or they always want subtitles

139
0:10:27.160000 --> 0:10:29.120000
in their language being shown.

140
0:10:29.120000 --> 0:10:35.880000
So the browser can look through this markup and identify which ones it has to turn on by

141
0:10:35.880000 --> 0:10:38.280000
default.

142
0:10:38.360000 --> 0:10:42.360000
Now in this case, I've used only Web VTT files.

143
0:10:42.360000 --> 0:10:50
The track layout, the way that we've defined track in HTML5 is actually generic.

144
0:10:50 --> 0:10:54.520000
It can be used for other types of files as well.

145
0:10:54.520000 --> 0:11:02.280000
TTML or SRT or any other formats that will be implemented.

146
0:11:02.360000 --> 0:11:11.200000
But the generic way that track works is in this way.

147
0:11:11.200000 --> 0:11:16.200000
Now once we've got it in the browser, we can actually support more than what is directly

148
0:11:16.200000 --> 0:11:19.800000
impossible as markup in the Web VTT file.

149
0:11:19.800000 --> 0:11:24.280000
Because now we've got the text in the browser and we can make use of all the functionality

150
0:11:24.280000 --> 0:11:32.040000
of the browser which has styling and the concurrent style sheet functionality available to it.

151
0:11:32.040000 --> 0:11:40.800000
So this kind of styling is also available if used in a browser to these queues.

152
0:11:40.800000 --> 0:11:48.760000
And the way in which this is being done is that there is a pseudo element in CSS called

153
0:11:48.760000 --> 0:11:51.240000
colon colon queue.

154
0:11:51.240000 --> 0:12:00.200000
And with that, pseudo element you can address, for example, classes in the queue markup and

155
0:12:00.200000 --> 0:12:06.480000
you can override the formatting that by default would be given.

156
0:12:06.480000 --> 0:12:12.320000
You can, for example, well in this case it's been turned red, uppercase, a different font

157
0:12:12.320000 --> 0:12:19.400000
family and a lighter weight.

158
0:12:19.400000 --> 0:12:20.600000
Now we've spoken a lot.

159
0:12:20.600000 --> 0:12:22.480000
We want to see a little bit of a demo here.

160
0:12:22.480000 --> 0:12:28.600000
And I've made a little bit of a demo which shows that we can do more than what's typically

161
0:12:28.600000 --> 0:12:30.480000
being used for captions right now.

162
0:12:30.480000 --> 0:12:36.080000
Most captions that are being used are pop-on captions which are captions that don't overlap

163
0:12:36.080000 --> 0:12:37.080000
in time.

164
0:12:37.080000 --> 0:12:40.040000
There's one piece of caption, one queue shown.

165
0:12:40.040000 --> 0:12:42.080000
It disappears and the next queue is brought up.

166
0:12:42.080000 --> 0:12:44.240000
That's pop-on.

167
0:12:44.240000 --> 0:12:47.920000
And that is the default way of rendering it.

168
0:12:47.920000 --> 0:12:55.200000
But we may have a very different style of providing captions as well which is traditionally

169
0:12:55.200000 --> 0:12:59.240000
been used mostly in live captioning.

170
0:12:59.240000 --> 0:13:00.680000
It's called roll up.

171
0:13:00.680000 --> 0:13:08.160000
So the queues will actually be added at the bottom and roll up and the old ones will disappear.

172
0:13:08.160000 --> 0:13:11.920000
So I've made a little example that shows how that can be done as well.

173
0:13:11.920000 --> 0:13:13.600000
Let's hope this works.

174
0:13:13.600000 --> 0:13:18.200000
I've heard about the Sargino project and I saw it online and I said, well, a lot of

175
0:13:18.200000 --> 0:13:20.040000
people are starting to talk about this.

176
0:13:20.040000 --> 0:13:21.440000
I should check it out.

177
0:13:21.440000 --> 0:13:27.760000
Because we wanted to make a tool for our students that was more modern, that was available

178
0:13:27.760000 --> 0:13:31.560000
on the market at the moment.

179
0:13:31.560000 --> 0:13:36
For me it was a case that this is a tool that I could see using myself and therefore

180
0:13:36 --> 0:13:39.400000
I could believe in actually helping me to get out to a wider world.

181
0:13:39.400000 --> 0:13:51.280000
So you could see that the captions were being pushed up.

182
0:13:51.360000 --> 0:14:06.080000
As they were being displayed, this is a very simple way of doing this kind of roll up.

183
0:14:06.080000 --> 0:14:10.680000
So as we're moving on, the next caption gets added to the bottom.

184
0:14:10.680000 --> 0:14:13.680000
This can be improved.

185
0:14:13.680000 --> 0:14:15.120000
This is just a very crude demo.

186
0:14:15.120000 --> 0:14:18.520000
But this can be improved with a bit more CSS in the browser.

187
0:14:18.520000 --> 0:14:25.680000
We can, for example, transition the text more slowly and then it would be more readable

188
0:14:25.680000 --> 0:14:28.040000
rather than it jumping there directly.

189
0:14:28.040000 --> 0:14:33.280000
There's a whole swag of CSS functionality available to us in the browser to make this

190
0:14:33.280000 --> 0:14:35.480000
look very nice.

191
0:14:35.480000 --> 0:14:42.760000
And the functionality is there and possible to be used.

192
0:14:42.760000 --> 0:14:47.560000
I've mentioned PaintOn and RollUp captions.

193
0:14:47.560000 --> 0:14:50.400000
I've mentioned PopOn and RollUp captions.

194
0:14:50.400000 --> 0:14:55.360000
I want to briefly also mention PaintOn captions even though that's a bit more of an exotic

195
0:14:55.360000 --> 0:14:56.360000
use case.

196
0:14:56.360000 --> 0:15:01.040000
But it's possible to be used in C8 captions.

197
0:15:01.040000 --> 0:15:06.840000
So we need to make sure that it's also possible to be represented in Web VTT.

198
0:15:06.840000 --> 0:15:13.120000
And what we've introduced for this kind of application is queue time stems.

199
0:15:13.120000 --> 0:15:19.440000
These queue time stems are basically just a time stem that is being included into the

200
0:15:19.440000 --> 0:15:27.440000
text and says when the text that comes afterwards will be activated.

201
0:15:27.440000 --> 0:15:31.440000
Here I've done it, pardon me, at the word level.

202
0:15:31.440000 --> 0:15:36.680000
I've put queue time stems in for every word.

203
0:15:36.680000 --> 0:15:40.200000
So every word would come up one after the other on the screen.

204
0:15:41.200000 --> 0:15:42.680000
However, the resolution is arbitrary.

205
0:15:42.680000 --> 0:15:47.640000
We could do that on every character if necessary.

206
0:15:47.640000 --> 0:15:55.800000
Interestingly enough, that can also be used for styling through CSS.

207
0:15:55.800000 --> 0:16:00.480000
There are the past and future pseudo selectors.

208
0:16:00.480000 --> 0:16:07.080000
And these selectors allow us, for example, to do something like Paint the old text in

209
0:16:07.080000 --> 0:16:12.360000
yellow, the new text in white with the text shadow.

210
0:16:12.360000 --> 0:16:15
And as it goes over, everything goes yellow.

211
0:16:15 --> 0:16:22.800000
And we know this kind of application, obviously, from Caroque, which bridges into these applications

212
0:16:22.800000 --> 0:16:27.880000
as well, into more modern timeline text applications.

213
0:16:27.880000 --> 0:16:34.440000
We can cover all of these use cases with the same approach.

214
0:16:34.440000 --> 0:16:38.360000
So that brings me to the end of the presentation.

215
0:16:38.360000 --> 0:16:46.600000
We regard Web VTT as a bridge between broadcast and the web of the future.

216
0:16:46.600000 --> 0:16:54.040000
We can support all of the C8608 captions, all of the features, possibly also some of the

217
0:16:54.040000 --> 0:16:57.480000
708 features.

218
0:16:57.480000 --> 0:17:01.920000
I think most of them, I haven't analyzed in detail, but most of the 708 features will

219
0:17:01.920000 --> 0:17:04.160000
be supported as well.

220
0:17:04.160000 --> 0:17:08.480000
It's a simplicity of editing, which we like about the Web VTT format.

221
0:17:08.480000 --> 0:17:09.480000
It's readable.

222
0:17:09.480000 --> 0:17:10.920000
You can read it here on screen.

223
0:17:10.920000 --> 0:17:16
There's not too much busyness as you're looking at it.

